         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">From all the pores rays crossed the directions, the lotus beds (looked) wholly golden colored.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">This world was wholly (illum)inated. The king Prabhāsa became amazed in the meantime. Here then</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the omniscients, Buddha-lords, teachers, having been ... started (to arrive) from all the four directions in wonderful ways,         </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">some were seen sitting in meditation, some others looking at the tree, some others ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">some others going for alms, some others freeing the beings, some others going by miraculous power, ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(some others) making wonders [and] teaching the Law to the gods. But others are saying these stanzas:</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> You (pl.) get started! You (pl.) leave! <hi>Sanskrit</hi> Join yourselves to the teaching of the Buddha-lord!</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Auf! [wtl. fangt an!] Geht hinaus [und] schließt euch der Lehre des Buddha an!</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">Come on! [lit. begin!] Go out [and] join the teaching of the Buddha!</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>370</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">You destroy (pl.) the army of death, <hi>Sanskrit</hi> as the elephant [destroys] a house made of reeds! </seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">Fragments <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns34"/>, <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns37"/> (including 38), <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns144"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns398"/> belong to the same manuscript. In this fragment the right margin is fairly well preserved, with a single vertical line 1,7 cm from the edge; no horizontal ruling is visible. The paper is torn, perforated and crumpled in many places. NS 37 completes NS 38 to the right. The whole fragment makes up the right part of a leaf.</note><note type="remarks">The lines b3-b4 contain the quotation and pada-like translation of the first of two famous Udānavarga stanzas, Udv. IV 37 and 38. This is a parallel in Tocharian A texts <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a258"/> a4-a5 and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a354"/> b5-b6.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">The form <hi>uppālṣi</hi> is nom. pl. m. of the adjective <hi>uppālṣe</hi>, which is metri causa for the expected nom. pl. f. <hi>uppālṣana</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a1 #a2" type="philcomment">The metrical part follows a meter of 4x12 syllables with a rhythm of 5/7.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">The form <hi>alyaiṅk</hi> stands for the nom. pl. m. <hi>alyaik</hi> which is found in all other instances. It is analogical from the obl. pl. m. which apparently shows a stem with nasal, cf. <hi>alyeṅkäṃ</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
